From f071a3fbe7da1aa69e3c49b29178d173cb18d3f2 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Micheal Waltz <micheal@ecliptik.com>
Date: Sat, 25 Apr 2026 12:52:11 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] sdl3: zoom.cpp INDEX8 dst surfaces need an explicit palette

SDL2 -> SDL3 migration regression. SDL_CreateSurface(w,h,INDEX8) in SDL3
no longer attaches a default palette to the new surface. zoom.cpp:324
created an INDEX8 dst surface, then the palette-copy block at 350-361
queried SDL_GetSurfacePalette on it and got NULL, so the if(_src_pal &&
_dst_pal) guard was always false and no palette ever got copied.

Surface::loadImage downstream then fed this paletteless INDEX8 surface
to SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface, which fails with "src does not have a
palette set". Every paletted image in the title screen rendered as a
null texture, then drawSurface flooded debug.log with
"Renderer::drawSurface: SDL_RenderTexture failed: Parameter texture
is invalid" once per blit attempt -- title screen never came up.

Fix: explicitly SDL_CreatePalette()/SDL_SetSurfacePalette() on rz_dst
before the colour copy. Release our local ref after attach since
SDL_SetSurfacePalette retains its own.

Why DOS needs this: the SDL3 DOS backend uses the same software
renderer path as the desktop SDL3 builds, so it inherits this exact
SDL3-API-divergence-from-SDL2 issue. Affects every paletted .pbm/.bmp
load.
---
 src/graphics/zoom.cpp | 21 ++++++++++++++++-----
 1 file changed, 16 insertions(+), 5 deletions(-)

diff --git a/src/graphics/zoom.cpp b/src/graphics/zoom.cpp
index 9ff0643..521c471 100644
--- a/src/graphics/zoom.cpp
+++ b/src/graphics/zoom.cpp
@@ -349,15 +349,26 @@ SDL_Surface *SDL_ZoomSurface(SDL_Surface *src, double zoom)
   {
     // Copy palette and colorkey info.
     // SDL3: palette is no longer hung off surface->format; query via SDL_GetSurfacePalette.
+    // SDL3 also no longer attaches a default palette to surfaces created with
+    // SDL_PIXELFORMAT_INDEX8 — SDL_GetSurfacePalette(rz_dst) returns NULL until
+    // we explicitly create + attach one. Without this, the palette-copy below
+    // silently no-ops and rz_dst exits with no palette, which then makes
+    // SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface() in Surface::loadImage fail with
+    // "src does not have a palette set".
     SDL_Palette *_src_pal = SDL_GetSurfacePalette(rz_src);
-    SDL_Palette *_dst_pal = SDL_GetSurfacePalette(rz_dst);
-    if (_src_pal && _dst_pal)
+    if (_src_pal)
     {
-      for (i = 0; i < _src_pal->ncolors; i++)
+      SDL_Palette *_dst_pal = SDL_CreatePalette(_src_pal->ncolors);
+      if (_dst_pal)
       {
-        _dst_pal->colors[i] = _src_pal->colors[i];
+        for (i = 0; i < _src_pal->ncolors; i++)
+        {
+          _dst_pal->colors[i] = _src_pal->colors[i];
+        }
+        // SDL_SetSurfacePalette retains its own reference; we can release ours.
+        SDL_SetSurfacePalette(rz_dst, _dst_pal);
+        SDL_DestroyPalette(_dst_pal);
       }
-      _dst_pal->ncolors = _src_pal->ncolors;
     }
 
     _zoomSurfaceY(rz_src, rz_dst);
-- 
